      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why Q Is the Most Dangerous Tile in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>Q's 10-point value is a double-edged sword. Play it well and you score massive points — get stuck with it at game end and you lose 10 points (a 20-point swing compared to playing it). This urgency makes Q strategy unique: you need to play it as soon as reasonably possible, even if the play isn't optimal.</p>
      <p>The biggest challenge is Q's traditional dependence on U. With only one U and one Q in the bag, the chances of having both simultaneously are low. That's why Q-without-U words are the most important vocabulary any serious player can memorise. They transform Q from a liability into a weapon.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Essential Q-Without-U Words</h2>
      <p>These words don't require U and are absolute lifesavers. Memorise them all — they turn a potential disaster into a scoring opportunity:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>QI (11 pts):</strong> The most important two-letter word in Scrabble. Playable almost anywhere on the board. Can be pluralised to QIS.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>QADI (14 pts), QAID (14 pts):</strong> Four-letter Q-no-U words that score identically. Both are Islamic/Arabic terms valid in tournament dictionaries.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>QAT (12 pts):</strong> A shrub chewed for stimulant effects. Short, high-scoring, and easy to place on tight boards.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>QOPH (18 pts):</strong> A Hebrew letter. The PH combo adds 7 points on top of Q's 10, making this a premium play.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>QWERTY (21 pts):</strong> Yes, the keyboard layout is a valid Scrabble word. Six letters, 21 points base value, no U required.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>TRANQ (14 pts):</strong> Informal for tranquiliser. This one ends with Q, making it useful for different board positions.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing Q-Words</h2>
      <p>Q demands a different strategic approach than any other tile:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Play Q early:</strong> Don't hold Q hoping for U or a perfect position. The risk of getting stuck with it at endgame outweighs the potential of a slightly better play later.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>QI is always playable:</strong> If there's any I on the board, QI can likely be played next to it. This is your emergency exit — never forget it exists.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Target triple-letter with Q:</strong> Q on a triple-letter square is 30 points just from that one tile. Always scan for TLS positions when holding Q.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Know the U position:</strong> Track whether U has been played. If U is in the discard pile, switch immediately to Q-no-U words.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Exchange as last resort:</strong> If you can't play Q and the bag has tiles left, exchanging just Q (keeping your other 6 tiles) is better than holding it for multiple turns.</span></li>
      </ul>

